{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LpqKdBxCuwLSFStGPTPtkq","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: create-test\n     3→description: Create a test file for a service or class. Use when scaffolding tests, adding test coverage, or creating test files.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Create Test\n     7→\n     8→Scaffold a test file for a service class with setup and test methods.\n     9→\n    10→## Usage\n    11→\n    12→```bash\n    13→jig run ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/recipe.yaml --vars '{\"service_name\": \"<ServiceName>\", \"module_path\": \"<module.path>\"}'\n    14→```\n    15→\n    16→## Variables\n    17→\n    18→- **service_name**: Name of the service class (e.g. `BookingService`)\n    19→- **module_path**: Python module path to the service (e.g. `services.booking`)\n    20→\n    21→Extract these from the user's request or by inspecting the source file.\n    22→\n    23→## Gotchas\n    24→\n    25→- If jig exits non-zero, it prints the rendered template to stderr. Use that output to apply changes manually.\n    26→- The output file is `tests/test_<service_name_snakecase>.py`.\n    27→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac8a33cf-5695-438d-bf16-a636603e8241","uuid":"d8785a04-2382-4f57-b334-56f765c7e52f"}
